So the final answer is \boxed{0.62} arcseconds. **Final Answer** The theoretical limiting angular resolution is \boxed{0.62} arcseconds. </think> To find the theoretical limiting angular resolution of an 8-inch (20.32 cm) optical telescope in the visible spectrum (5000 Å = 500 nm), we use the diffraction limit formula: \[ \theta = 1.22 \frac{\lambda}{D} \] where: - \(\lambda\) is the wavelength of light (500 nm = \(5 \times 10^{-7}\) m), - \(D\) is the diameter of the telescope's aperture (8 inches = 0.2032 m). 1. Convert the wavelength to meters: \(500 \text{ nm} = 5 \times 10^{-7} \text{ m}\). 2. Calculate the angular resolution in radians: \[ \theta = 1.22 \times \frac{5 \times 10^{-7} \text{ m}}{0.2032 \text{ m}} \approx 1.22 \times 2.4606 \times 10^{-6} \approx 3.0012 \times 10^{-6} \text{ radians} \] 3. Convert radians to arcseconds (1 radian = 206,265 arcseconds): \[ \theta \approx 3.0012 \times 10^{-6} \times 206,265 \approx 0.619 \text{ arcseconds} \] 4. Round to two significant figures: 0.62 arcseconds. Thus, the theoretical limiting angular resolution is \(\boxed{0.62}\) arcseconds.
